<TITLE> War crimes agency seeks power to arrest </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Mar 28 (bdnews24.com)Chief of the war crimes investigating agency Abdul Matin said Sunday that the existing war crimes legislation needs to be amended to make the body effective. Currently, the agency does not possess the authority to arrest someone under the International Crimes Tribunal Act of 1973, he said after assuming office of the newly created agency. Matin also told reporters about the modus operandi of the new agency and how it would proceed aimed at making sure that alleged war criminals are brought to justice. "New rules need to be formulated in line with the Act so that the agency have the power to arrest anyone allegedly involved in the crimes against humanity during the liberation war," Matin added. On Mar 25, the government announced the long-awaited formation of the war crimes tribunal, investigative and prosecution teams just hours before the commemoration of the Black Night of March 25 when Pakistani forces killed thousands of innocent civilians in 1971. The newly formed three-member tribunal, the seven-member investigating agency and the 12-member panel of prosecutors are set to begin their work from Monday. Chairman of the tribunal justice Md Nizamul Huq, and members justice Fazle Kabir and justice AKM Zahir Ahmed took office Sunday; among the 12 prosecutors, Mosharraf Hossain Kajal and Sanjida Khanam also joined work. While asked about the procedure of their work, the probe agency chief said, "First, we'll collect informationaccording to the complaints and from archives at home and abroad, newspapers, video footage, cassettes etc." The agency will also look into the lists from different sources, he said, adding that "Lists prepared by the Sector Commanders' Forum and the Ghatak Dalal Nirmul Committee will also be taken into consideration." bd
